<p>
@EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}} which indicates the speaker's belief that something will happen (or happened).

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{come}}ru @EM{{hazu}}desuyo. kinou @KJ{{electricity^tale}}ga arimashitakara.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'm sure he'll come. I received a phone call from him yesterday.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
An expectation that something will not be the case can be expressed either by negating the sentence before @EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{kura-ku}}sanha@KT{{pa-texi-}}ni@KJ{{going}}kanai@EM{{hazu}}da.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I expect that Mr. Clark is going to the party.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
Alternatively the sentence can be followed by @EM{{@HI{{hazu}}}} @HI{{ha/ganai}}.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{kura-ku}}sanha@KT{{pa-texi-}}ni@KJ{{going}}ku@EM{{hazu}}ganai.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It is improbable that Mr. Clark will go to the party.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
The latter construction carries the heavier weight.
</p>

